            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Solana Rojas was raised in Fresno, a child of two distinct worlds. Her father, a meticulous Mexican-American carpenter, taught her the value of skilled hands and structure. Her mother, a white high school art teacher, filled their home with books on Renaissance painters and Impressionist light. Solana absorbed both lessons, spending her youth equally comfortable with a paintbrush and styling her friends' hair for school dances, seeing the beauty in both composition and craft.\n\nPressured gently by her mother\u2019s academic values, Solana pursued an Art History degree at UC Santa Cruz. She loved the theory, but a post-graduation internship at a sterile gallery left her feeling disconnected. The art was behind glass, distant from life. The turning point came when she helped a friend, heartbroken after a breakup, with a dramatic hair color transformation. Seeing the immediate joy and confidence she could create was a revelation. It wasn't just hair; it was wearable, living art. This realization prompted her bold pivot: enrolling in cosmetology school.\n\nNow, Solana thrives in San Francisco. She found her niche at a boutique salon in Hayes Valley, where her Art History background is her secret weapon. She talks to clients about the soft pastels of Rococo for a delicate blonde or the bold, clashing colors of German Expressionism for an edgy cut. Her approach has earned her a loyal clientele and a comfortable income.\n\nSolana lives in a bright, second-floor apartment in the Mission District with a roommate, a short Muni ride from work. Her daily routine is a city rhythm: the screech of the J Church train, the hum of hairdryers, and evenings spent exploring the vibrant tapestry of murals and taquerias that remind her of her heritage. Her social life is a warm mix of salon colleagues and friends met through local art walks. Her dream is to one day open her own small studio, a space that feels more like an artist\u2019s loft than a salon, where she can continue to sculpt confidence and paint joy onto the people of the city she now calls home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was nine, the scent of cedar and turpentine thick in the Fresno heat. Her father was showing her how to follow the grain in a piece of wood with a chisel, to reveal the shape hiding inside. Later, her mother showed her a book on Bernini, pointing to the folds of a marble dress. In that moment, seeing the flow in both wood and stone, Solana understood. Craft and art were the same language. It taught her to see the potential form in everything, a lesson she would carry into every haircut.\n\n2.\nThe gallery internship was crushing her spirit. After work one day, her friend Maya sat crying in her kitchen, shattered by a breakup. On impulse, Solana grabbed the scissors. Snipping away the matted ends and mixing a bold, coppery red felt more real than any curated exhibit. When she turned Maya to the mirror, the gasp of joy was electric. It was immediate, tangible art. That night, she quit the gallery. The experience cemented her belief that true art wasn't for walls; it was for people, a tool for immediate transformation.\n\n3.\nHer first big risk in the Hayes Valley salon was a nervous corporate lawyer who only ever wore beige. The woman wanted blonde, but was terrified. Solana didn\u2019t show her a swatch book; she opened her phone to a Rococo painting by Fragonard, describing the soft, powdered light. The woman trusted her. When she saw the final, delicate blonde, she teared up. In that moment, Solana knew her unique approach wasn't a gimmick; it was a gift. It solidified her confidence as a true artist in her new city.\n\n4.\nOne evening after a long Saturday shift, she was walking down Clarion Alley. She stopped before a vibrant mural depicting farm workers, their faces etched with the same dignity she saw in her father\u2019s. The smell from a nearby taqueria was so exactly like her grandmother\u2019s kitchen it made her ache. It was a profound click of belonging. The Mission wasn't just a cool neighborhood; it was an extension of her own story, a place where her Mexican-American heritage was painted on the walls for everyone to see.\n\n5.\nLate one Tuesday, looking out her Mission apartment window, her hands still ached from a day of styling. The familiar, metallic screech of the J Church train punctuated the quiet. She thought of the day's clients, each one leaving a little taller, a little brighter. She didn't picture a future salon of chrome and black leather, but one with worn wooden floors like her father\u2019s workshop and huge, north-facing windows like a painter\u2019s studio. This quiet vision wasn\u2019t just a dream; it felt like a blueprint, her inevitable next step."
